Guidelines for BDD object-15 Value: That CBT is the standard approach I believe
Anything else to tell us object-19 Value: I think it can be easy to spot when it's a focus on a specific feature such as a nose, skin, hair etc. But less easy to spot when it crosses over with eating disorders or gender identity difficulties. I do wonder if many of the young people we treat with eating disorders using the Maudsley Approach are actually experiencing body dysmorphia, I have worked with many young people who have been diagnosed with anorexia but many of their behaviours are focused specifically around losing weight on their tummy, which seems to be the main preoccupation of their eating disorder.

Guidelines for BDD object-15 Value: NICE guidelines recommend CBT and SSRI treatment.
Protocols for BDD object-17 Value:
A Therapist's Guide for the Treatment of BDD
CBT for BDD (Veale?)
Anything else to tell us object-19 Value: I feel that the characterisation of body dysmorphia as being situated within an individual's faulty cognitions is a bit of a limited way of viewing this problem, and one that risks problematising a child's suffering. Understanding what it is a child is seeking to protect or move towards in their life by enacting a campaign against their own appearance is crucial for developing a treatment plan that does more than assuage the anxieties of the adults surrounding them.
